"},"da":{"–1245":"–1245","1190–Male":"1190–Afdød","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–Female":"Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","–1240":"–1240","1209–1270":"1209–1270","1212–1266":"1212–1266","–1304":"–1304","1165–Male":"1165–Afdød","1190":"1190","1304":"1304","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"fra august 1189 til 1219"},"nl":{"–1245":"–1245","1190–Male":"1190–Overleden","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–Female":"Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","–1240":"–1240","1209–1270":"1209–1270","1212–1266":"1212–1266","–1304":"–1304","1165–Male":"1165–Overleden","1190":"1190","1304":"1304","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"van augustus 1189 to 1219"},"en":{"–1245":"–1245","1190–Male":"1190–Deceased","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","–1240":"–1240","1209–1270":"1209–1270","1212–1266":"1212–1266","–1304":"–1304","1165–Male":"1165–Deceased","1190":"1190","1304":"1304","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"from August 1189 to 1219","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marshall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: usually an occupational name ‘farrier’, occasionally a status name ‘chief official of a royal household or court; a high officer of state’, from Middle English <i>mareshal</i> and Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>. An even wider range of meanings is found in some other languages: compare for example Polish <b>Marszałek</b> (see   Marszalek  ). This name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century. It is also borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Marschall  .","Americanized form of French   Mercier  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marchel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jacek, Ryszard.  German Ernst.","Polish: probably from French <i>maréchal</i> or Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>, which was originally an occupational name for someone who was in charge of the horses of a household, later a military rank for a senior general. See   Marshall   and compare   Marszalek  ."]},{"name":"Mercier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Gaston, Lucien, Aurele, Jacques, Normand, Laurent, Michel, Valmont.","French and Channel Islands (Jersey): occupational name for a merchant, from Old French <i>mercier</i>, from Late Latin <i>merciarius</i> (an agent derivative of <i>merx</i>, genitive <i>mercis</i> ‘merchandise’). This name was also taken to England by Huguenot refugees. Compare   Marshall   and   Mercy  ."]},{"name":"Maniscalco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Vito, Sal, Antonio, Ignazio, Carmelo, Francesco, Gaspare, Saverio, Antonino, Carlo, Damiano.","Italian (southern): occupational name from <i>maniscalco</i> ‘farrier’, altered from <i>marescalco</i> by folk etymology, probably influenced by <i>mano</i> ‘hand’, from medieval Latin <i>mariscalcus</i>, <i>marescalcus</i>. Compare   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marchal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gilles, Jacques, Maryse, Philippe, Pierre, Veronique.","French and Walloon: status name or occupational name from Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The term is of ancient Germanic origin (from <i>marah</i> ‘horse, mare’ + <i>scalc</i> ‘servant’) and was originally applied to a man who looked after horses. In the Middle Ages it also came to be used on the one hand as an occupational name for a farrier, and on the other as a status name for an officer of state, in particular a member of a royal household with military responsibilities. Compare English   Marshall   and 2 below.","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland, and is found mainly in Glamorgan, Wales."]},{"name":"Maskell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  , derived from Middle English, Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i> ‘marshal’. The first element in the placename Mascallsbury (Essex) derives from the surname of a 13th-century individual named Robert <i>le Marescal</i>."]},{"name":"Marszalek","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Piotr, Alicja, Andrzej, Eugeniusz, Henryk, Jerzy, Kazimierz, Mieczyslaw, Wieslaw, Zbigniew, Zofia, Zygmunt.","Polish (<b>Marszałek</b>): occupational or status name from the vocabulary word <i>marszałek</i> ‘marshal’, denoting anything from a high court official, a field marshal, or the chairman of the Polish parliament, to the senior servant in a great household. Compare English   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marshell","meanings":["English: variant of   Marshall  ."]},{"name":"Marschall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Hedwig, Juergen, Reinhard, Theresia, Wilfried.","German: occupational name for a man in the service of a member of the nobility, originally one who looked after the horses, Middle High German <i>marschalc</i> (from <i>mar(c)</i> ‘noble horse’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant’). In time the term came to be used for a military rank or a certain court official. Compare   Marshall  .","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marshal","meanings":["(1997: 186;2007: 634; 2010: NA)","English and Scottish: variant of   Marshall  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Matilda Marshall was born as the daughter of Sir William Marshall and Countess Of Pembroke Isabel De Clare. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Earl Of Surrey William Of Warenne. She died in 1245."},"et":{"–1245":"–1245","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–1240":"–1240","1209–1270":"1209–1270","1212–1266":"1212–1266","–1304":"–1304","1165–Male":"1165–Surnud","1190":"1190","1304":"1304","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"august 1189 kuni 1219"},"fi":{"–1245":"–1245","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–1240":"–1240","1209–1270":"1209–1270","1212–1266":"1212–1266","–1304":"–1304","1165–Male":"1165–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1304":"1304","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"vuodesta elokuu 1189 vuoteen 1219"},"fr":{"–1245":"–1245","1190–Male":"1190–Décédé","1209–1245":"1209–1245","–1241":"–1241","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","–1240":"–1240","1209–1270":"1209–1270","1212–1266":"1212–1266","–1304":"–1304","1165–Male":"1165–Décédé","1190":"1190","1304":"1304","1245":"1245","1212":"1212","1266":"1266","1165":"1165","1241":"1241","1240":"1240","1270":"1270","1209":"1209","August 1189 to 1219":"du août 1189 au 1219","lifeSummary":"Maud Matilda Marshall est née, fille de Sir William Marshall et Countess Of Pembroke Isabel De Clare. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec Earl Of Surrey William Of Warenne. Elle est décédée en 1245."},"de":{"–1245":"–1245","1190–Male":"1190–Versto